Short answer

Simulation can stimulate growth when it does one or more of these:
	•	changes state
	•	changes behavior
	•	changes training volume or quality
	•	changes hormone-relevant context signals
	•	changes recovery, confidence, and consistency

But it has limits.

A simulation can strongly affect:
	•	attention
	•	arousal
	•	stress response
	•	motivation
	•	motor learning
	•	pain perception
	•	expectation
	•	identity and self-model

It can indirectly change hormonal environment through those routes.

What it usually cannot do by itself is fully replace:
	•	mechanical loading for muscle and bone
	•	nutrition
	•	sleep
	•	actual tissue damage/repair cycles
	•	real environmental chemistry

So the right model is not:

simulation magically causes growth

It is:

simulation changes the control system, which changes physiology, behavior, and adaptation

That’s the bridge.

